{
  "query": "What are the overall effects of growing cover crops in arable fields on Mediterranean farmland, considering soil health and crop production?",
  "relevant_summary": "Across Mediterranean-type settings (including studies from Italy, Spain, France and Israel), winter cover crops often increased soil organic matter in some or all comparisons, though one Italian study reported inconsistent differences (sometimes more, sometimes less) [1345]. Soil nitrogen was higher in some comparisons but overall results were inconsistent; using legumes as cover crops increased soil nitrogen relative to non-legumes in multiple studies [1345]. Soil biological indicators frequently improved: microbial biomass increased in some studies, bacteria and fungi were higher in Spain, and beneficial mycorrhizal spores/species were higher in Italy, while earthworm responses were mixed [1345]. Physical soil properties and erosion tended to improve: cover crops reduced soil erosion in Israel and increased water-stable aggregates in Spain [1345]. Hydrologically, findings were mixed: in Spain one study found greater cover crop water use and another no difference; across France, Israel and Spain several studies found reduced water losses via runoff, drainage or evaporation, although one Spanish study found greater drainage with winter cover crops; nitrate leaching was reduced in Spain in some comparisons [1357]. Crop production outcomes were variable: studies from Spain and Italy reported lower, higher, or no change in cash crop yields with winter cover crops in different comparisons; however, several studies reported higher yields when legumes were used as winter cover crops compared to non-legumes [1351].",
  "action_ids": [
    "1345",
    "1357",
    "1351"
  ]
}

